The group of managers mumbled, â€œNo.â€
â€œWhat is it then?â€ I asked.
Finally, one of the more senior managers spoke up with a serious answer: â€œIâ€™d feel pretty stupid asking. Our CEO is smart and has a lot of experience. She gets this business.â€
â€œOK,â€ I shot back. â€œSo youâ€™re all just scared to look stupid?â€
Heads nodded in a universal yes.
I nodded as well, now more fully understanding the issue. No one wants to look stupid, especially in front of the boss. â€œLet me ask you this,â€ I continued. â€œWhen you canâ€™t explain the reason behind this new compensation plan to your sales force, how does that make you look?â€
â€œStupid and scared,â€ the class clown responded.
â€œExactly!â€ I shot back, in jest. But I knew a simple, easy way to solve the problem had been uncovered.
That afternoon I swung by the CEOâ€™s office. She was meeting with the companyâ€™s president of sales.
â€œHow is the workshop going?â€ the CEO inquired.
â€œItâ€™s going pretty well,â€ I said. â€œYou have a solid crew of managers.â€
â€œAbsolutely. They are a great group,â€ replied the CEO.
â€œHow is your relationship with them?â€ I asked.
â€œOh, I think it is very strong with most of them. Some of the newer ones I donâ€™t know all that well yet, but as a whole, I have a good relationship with our managers,â€ the CEO answered.
â€œDo they ever confront you on anything or ask questions?â€ I asked.
