A common misperception among military leaders or corporate senior executives, this was an example of a boss who didnâ€™t fully comprehend the weight of her position. In her mind, she was fairly laid back, open to questions, comments, and suggestions from people. She talked about maintaining an â€œopen-door policy.â€ But in the minds of her sales managers, she was still The Boss: experienced, smart, and most important, powerful. That position demanded a high level of reverenceâ€”so high, in fact, that for an employee to question her ideas seemed disrespectful. None of them were comfortable questioning her, even though none of the midlevel managers actually worried about losing their jobs because they asked a question. But they were certainly worried about looking bad in front of The Boss.
â€œIâ€™m not sure they are as comfortable confronting you or opening up to you as you think,â€ I stated bluntly.
